model %>%

  • layer_dense(units = 256, activation = 'relu', input_shape = c(784)) %>%
  • layer_dropout(rate = 0.4) %>%
  • layer_dense(units = 128, activation = 'relu') %>%
  • layer_dropout(rate = 0.3) %>%
  • layer_dense(units = 10, activation = 'softmax')
    Show Traceback

Rerun with Debug
Error in py_call_impl(callable, dots$args, dots$keywords) :
ValueError: Layer dense_1 was called with an input that isn't a symbolic tensor. Received type: <class 'keras.engine.se

However, this was tensorflow 1.10.0 since 1.10.1 does not install (see error at beginning of post).
Thanks.

body:
Yes, dplyr was loaded via tidyverse. I also loaded library(magrittr).  
Here is the error message (this time from the MNIST example from the Tensorflow R webpage: 
model %>% 
+   layer_dense(units = 256, activation = 'relu', input_shape = c(784)) %>% 
+   layer_dropout(rate = 0.4) %>% 
+   layer_dense(units = 128, activation = 'relu') %>%
+   layer_dropout(rate = 0.3) %>%
+   layer_dense(units = 10, activation = 'softmax')
 Show Traceback
 
 Rerun with Debug
 Error in py_call_impl(callable, dots$args, dots$keywords) : 
  ValueError: Layer dense_1 was called with an input that isn't a symbolic tensor. Received type: <class 'keras.engine.se

However, this was tensorflow 1.10.0 since 1.10.1 does not install (see error at beginning of post).
Thanks.
